    <h1>BAKUCHIOL</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201023/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-23"><time>2020-10-23</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | STYLE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>This kooky-sound­ing in­gre­di­ent has piqued in­ter­est for de­liv­er­ing the same ben­e­fits as retinol – mi­nus the po­ten­tial ag­gra­va­tion.</p>
    <p>A nat­u­rally de­rived ac­tive in­gre­di­ent found in the seeds and leaves of the pso­ralea coryli­fo­lia plant, it has been shown to im­prove the ap­pear­ance of lines and wrin­kles, im­prove skin tex­ture and boost col­la­gen and elastin pro­duc­tion.</p>
    <p>While some have dared to call it a “nat­u­ral retinol” or “retinol al­ter­na­tive”, bakuchiol is not an ex­act sub­sti­tute for retinol. But its gen­tler prop­er­ties make it a safer op­tion for all skin types, as well as for preg­nant women.</p>
    <p>TRY:</p>
    <p>1. Bybi Beauty Bakuchiol Booster, $23</p>
    <p>2. PSA Skin Mid­night Courage Rose­hip & Bakuchiol Retinol Night Oil, $58</p>
    <p>3. Sigi Skin Dream Cap­sule, $82</p>

